I don't like to give bad reviews but this one is just way too bad I felt the other buyers on Amazon should know so they can purchase a different drive.
To start with, I never had a flash drive get as hot as this one and I have many other drives both old and new and different capacities some plastic some metal. I fear the heat will kill it sooner than any other drive. The reason it gets so hot is because the components inside are being clocked at a speed that is too high, much higher than they were designed to handle. They are being overclocked. What is strange is that even so, this drive is actually very slow compared to other drives that are said to have a speed over 100MB per second. For very large files the top speed was 35MB per second and I could live with that, but for a group of small files the speed drops to a mere 2MB per second. Yes, that is a 2 not 20. So if you transfer a 200 MB file it might take 10 seconds, but if you transfer 1000 200k files it would take 100 seconds if you are lucky, and that's still a total of 200MB. This means it may work for you if you only use it for large files unless it burns itself out due to the intense self heating. You also don't want to touch it right away let it cool before pulling it out of the USB connector, and while you are waiting search for a better drive on Amazon.
Note:
I use Crystal Disk Mark for speed test results but also do manually timed file copy and paste operations to back those results up with real world usage results.
Also note I have other SanDisk drives that work reasonably well.

This is a step up from a previous dock that I had as it lets me run multiple monitors (2 in my case: 1x 27" and 1x 24") at 4K resolution.  A prior poster mentioned he had to run his monitors at refresh rate of 30hz, and while I was able to run one at 30 and one at 60, I was noticing significant lag and delays with the mouse (wired, wireless, or touchpad didn't matter) that only happened when connected to the dock.  Dropping the one monitor from 60hz to 30hz solved the issue.  This dock has otherwise been great, making it very easy to connect and disconnect my laptop.  I only wish it had a few more USB 3.0 ports, as I still have quite of few of those devices vs USB C.

Unfortunately the screen protector has a significant amount of glare present in bright environments, making it really hard to use in an office environment or when outside (keep in mind the iPad has anti glare coating on the screen itself, and doesn‚Äôt get super bright as to drown out the glare). Additionally, the installation stickers were not nearly sticky enough to be useful, meaning that I had to source the stickers from another screen protector I had.
Fit perfectly and easy install

Overall, this product is as advertised and mine arrived with no defects. I love having a wide variety of ports as well as enough of each to plug in everything I need to.  However it is not able to support high refresh rates despite having the correct ports which is why it only gets 4/5 stars. My display is a 165hz UHD gaming monitor and I only get 60hz when plugged into the docking station so I have to plug the monitor in directly to the laptop. Minor inconvenience but something to note. In addition, power delivery is too weak for my primary laptop (Dell 5550) but enough for my work laptop (Lenovo ThinkPad T14). It does the trick for an affordable dock especially considering most alternatives cost more than double. If you really need better power delivery and high refresh rates for gaming, you may want to consider a more expensive option. If you're looking for an affordable option to keep cables organized and avoid plugging and unplugging a bunch of cables, this may be a good option.

The Insta360 Link is likely the Best Webcam I‚Äôve ever used. Though I have never used another gimbal-based camera, it is truly a quality webcam with some pretty slick features. Over the course of the past week or so, I‚Äôve been using the Insta360 Link to record videos, and have video calls through Skype and Zoom. I also wanted to test it as a second camera angle for use during my live stream which I‚Äôll get into as well.

Upon unboxing the Link, I plugged it in using the included (maybe 3-foot long) USB-C to USB-C cable and it quickly installed the drivers and I was up and running. Unlike other cameras that I‚Äôve used that had a shorter cable, this one seemed like the perfect length to not only use with a laptop but have enough length when using with a desktop setup located on the floor. Obviously if you needed to put the camera at a longer distance, you could pick up a cable from one of the popular manufacturers here on Amazon.

First off, as I mentioned, there are a number of slick features that combine the flexibility of the gimbal-based hardware with the power of the Insta360 software. Besides the things that you would expect in a webcam like auto exposure, auto-white balance, etc, the Link offers a really novel usage of A.I. motion tracking with gesture control to enable or modify certain features.

When enabled in the app, hold up your hand and the LED light on the webcam flashes from its normal Green to Blue to indicate that motion tracking is turned on. You can also do this by simply single tapping on the front of the camera base and then tap again to turn it off. I gotta say, this is a nice implementation to toggle the gesture control feature on and off.

There are three modes that you can modify in the app including Normal (default), Fast and Slow. During my usage, I pretty much stuck with either Normal or Slow as I think fast could make people on the other side of your video call a little nauseous. If you think you will be moving around at a normal speed, then Normal is perfect. However, if you only plan on making small movements, use the slow setting. The camera did a great job to track and follow me, pretty much without any lag.

There are two other gestures that you can use including holding your left hand up in the shape of an L to enable zoom. While holding your hand in that position, either raise or lower the ‚ÄúL‚Äù to zoom in or out, respectively. It works pretty well but it worked a little better when I was located 3-4 feet away from the camera vs when I had my laptop on my lap. There is also a whiteboard mode that you can enable by making the ‚ÄúV‚Äù gesture with your hand. I tried it and it turned on the mode but since I don‚Äôt have a whiteboard, couldn‚Äôt really test this feature.

There are a few other modes that you can enable in the app including a slight downward angle which is good if you are trying to capture an image of your keyboard or something right in front of the monitor. There is also a true ‚Äúoverhead‚Äù view that would be incredibly handy if you had the proper setup to utilize this mode. I definitely have to play with this one more. I believe that Insta360 offers a specific extendable tripod for the camera that can be screwed into the quarter-20 thread on the bottom.

Overall, the color and brightness is good and sharp, especially in a properly lit scene. If you are using a ring light or something like the Elgato Key Light, Godox ES45 or the Boling P1 Vlogger, this camera will shine and make you look fantastic. If you are using the camera in a darker environment, you may have to tweak the brightness to your liking. I had to bump it up by 6 or 7 notches in the app to get it where I was happy. Again, in a bright setting, the HDR looked great but it was a bit too dark for my taste when the lights were turned off. I think this is more of a function of HDR vs the way the camera handles it.

As I mentioned, I‚Äôm also a live streamer, so I wanted to see if it would work with my current setup. I personally use a software called VMix and it did struggle a bit with the video, making it look a little jumpy. I THINK this is more of a problem with VMix since the other 2 or 3 webcam‚Äôs I‚Äôve tried also faced the same issue. When I opened up OBS, and added the Link as a camera source, the video was smooth as normal. I‚Äôd love to see Insta360 contact VMix to see if some optimization could be done.

Final Thoughts: I REALLY like this webcam and think it would make a great addition for anyone that is constantly on conference calls, especially if you tend to move around a bit. Comparing to the video in my Dell XPS 15 laptop and it truly not a fair fight. Exposure, color and the ability to enable motion tracking are all really well done.

I searched high and low for this desktop computer. I first saw a similar pc on Woot, but unfortunately, it was a disaster, the unit came missing accessories and worse damage. The worst part of the experience was the seller has the monopoly of Lenovo refurbs on Woot, Amazon, Tanga and ebay. So, when I saw Tekrefurbs, a small family outfit, I was delighted and thus, they did not disappoint. The best part of the purchase, free shipping and a lesser price than elsewhere. It is a refurb so I do expect scratches and dents, not a problem. Furthermore, it was a breeze to set up and as a work from home person, I was able to purchase a gadget to attach two monitors. The version of windows 10 installed is the most current version so old Logitech wireless mouse and keyboard may not be compatible with the windows 10 software installed. Moreover, the unit is lightening fast in accessing files and browsing the internet. Luckily, the desktop unit came with a wired mouse and keyboard. To be honest, I was surprised to find that wired mouse and keyboard are still around in this day and age. Suffice it to say, they both serve my needs. So if you are living on a work from home budget, then this desktop is for you. I do recommend Lenovo units, this is my second unit purchased and as soon as disposable funds become available I will be purchasing one of the i7 units for my personal use.
PS. The unit was shipped without the additional storage (1T) but I called up the company and they promptly shipped an external hard drive to my and I received it the next day. I am very satisfied with the product and the service that came along with it.

Only odd thing that seems to only occur with these earbuds that some might find annoying is: they are very conductive to static electricity.

I think that the metal case on them may be in some way grounded to or at least very close to the speaker driver inside.
What this means is that if you shift in your seat and are wearing a static jacket or sweater, and are in a low humidity environment, and your phone is plugged into a charger (makes this happen more), you will be zapped in the ears by static electricity and hear a few pops.
Your computer monitors may black out for a few seconds when this happens as the interference is enough to disrupt the video signal, despite this happening on your phone and wall charger.

I've never had this issue with other metal or plastic earbuds.

Despite this I still like the earbuds so will continue to use them until they eventually fail.

I ordered this antenna mount to install an outdoor PoE mesh network access point for my Starlink service. I was looking for a sturdy mount that would hold to the weather. The Proxicast Pro-Grade J-Max 100% Solid Stainless Steel Antenna Mount more than filled the task. I chose the stainless steel mount over the aluminum since it was only a few dollars more. Also, I wanted to increase the height of the mast by adding additional tubing, so the stainless steel should be able to carry any extra weight easily.

The mount was straightforward to install. After installing the base support to the wall, there are only 4 bolts to insert and tighten. However, a couple of the base's mounting holes are directly behind the J arm. If you want to use these, you may have to assemble the unit in place rather than on the ground. The two small bolts holding the arm have to be slid in from the inside to the J arm tube. It was tricky holding the bolt inside the tube to line it up with the provided hole while standing on a ladder.

I have vinyl siding, so I wanted to use the facia board on the soffit. The base support is a bit large (over 7 inches) and my facia boards are not that wide. I wound up using a front corner that gave me more surface area. Since I wanted to add to the mast height by a few feet, I used 1-inch PVC schedule 40 pipe. That size was almost perfect and slid fairly snuggly into the Proxicast J arm. I inserted the PVC pipe to the bend in the J-arm and added a few feet of length. I used 2 additional 1/4-inch bolts to secure the pipe. All in all, a very solid installation.

I bought the modem/mesh router combo. The modem and one router works well enough. Setting up an additional router for a mesh network doesn't work.

On a Galaxy S22 Ultra, the app takes over a minute to even turn on. When it does, it usually fails to recognize that it is connected to the network it is supposed to manage, despite the fact that the phone is using that wifi. As a result, you can't make any changes to the network. In the rare instances where it does recognize the connection, it invariably can't successfully navigate through all the steps to get the second satellite connected. After about 50 attempts, I managed to get the second router to successfully mesh. After 2 hours, it inexplicably became disconnected and would never work again.

Customer service is completely useless. There's a live chat function that is just permanently unavailable. If you manage to actually find the phone number, which is buried on their website and locked behind a model and SN warranty verification, they are unable to help. After an afternoon trying every version of "reset it" known to man, tech support told me to get a replacement from Amazon.

I have no reason to believe that a replacement is going to work any better. The issue does not seem to be the device, it seems to be the software that powers it.

What do I like? The fact that not only do these earbuds provide absolutely amazing sound (it feels like you're in a live performance because of the separation of the different sounds, so the music feels like it is literally all around you), but, finally, some genius somewhere came up with a comfortable design that actually stay in my ears securely - I am hooked on these earbuds!

What don't I like? Well, as with all Apple products, you are supposed to know how to use these right out of the box with minimal instruction. Yes, I read what there was of the "user guide", but I finally had to go online to find out how in the heck to turn the volume up and down - you have to ask Siri! And my pair came set at an uncomfortably high level of sound, so I was really anxious to know how to accomplish this feat. There are many different sources to get information online, but for this price you would think they would include instructions for something as vital as controlling the volume. I don't mind that they can't be charged wirelessly, that for me is not a deal breaker.

I will have to say the noise canceling works really, really well - this is my first pair of true noise canceling earbuds - but as a single older female, I'm not sure how much I will use that feature, as I am very aware of my personal security at all times. It's nice to have, though. I walked next to my usually noisy furnace while it was running and couldn't hear anything but the music I was listening to - I thought that was awesome. Amazing what they can do with technology.

If you're a really devoted, expert music fan, you might not like these - I read some reviews that complained about various "defects" in the sound quality, but my ear isn't educated enough to pick those up, if they are really there. There is just no pleasing some people at any price point, so I'll take these and be very happy to have them! They work for me, so that's my main issue right there. And they stay in my ears! Oh, one more thing - I started out, as recommended, with the Medium ear tips, but noticed by this morning that my ears were very slightly irritated, so I changed them out for the Small size. Perfect, with no loss of sound quality.

Great kit from iFixit.  This is the first item I ever bought from them, and I'm not disappointed.  I really just wanted a nice screwdriver with some common bits I could use for phone and computer repair.  I already have a million pry tools lying around from other screen kits and such, but I will say this blue pry tool is the most sturdy one I've ever used.  Very durable and hard plastic.  Yes it will wear down eventually, but not as quickly as the cheap ones if you've ever used them.  Tweezers are also very fine and sharp!  I know because I sliced my thumb up really nice with them! :D  Great item as well!  Tips will bend if you're too harsh on them so just be careful if you're trying to use them as mini "pliers".  Suction cup is probably the most sturdy and strong I've ever used too.  The double-suction removal tool they sell is probably more practical, but I have no issue spending the extra 10 seconds holding the device at a certain angle to get the pry tool underneath the screen.  Another fantastic item.  Screwdriver is very sturdy as well, and the bits are very nice and come magnetized!  A wonderful feature after using non-magnetized bits for SO long.  I found that after excessive use the magnets ability will slowly wear away, but one of those magnetizers for bits will make it good as new again.  Black spudger tool is very nice too, I find it very handy in certain situations, and once again, it seems to be better quality than the other cheap ones you can find in repair kits.  Overall, iFixit takes what was good in repair tools, and upgrades the quality by 10x.  To say I'm paying for the name is probably fair.  This kit could easily be $19.99.  But for the quality and brands reputation, I'd say I made a great decision going with this kit.  Repairs iPhones, Samsungs, Computers, Controllers.  An all around beast of a portable kit!

Easy to pair, very simple operation, and shockingly good sound from such a small package. As an owner of a Marshall amp, the Action III has the same aesthetics with the gold face and knobs, the vintage grille cloth, and the thick heavy cabinet. It even has a little something that their amps don't. Instead of a line on the bass, treble, and volume knobs that displays the level, the Action III has LEDs around the knobs which light up as you move clockwise. It's smaller than a shoebox and my fingertips reach around the top, but it's difficult to pick up one handed due to its weight. You're not going to accidentally knock it off of your table or counter without some effort.

This speaker is not rechargeable. It‚Äôs powered by an AC cord. This may be a disadvantage to some because you won‚Äôt be taking it on a picnic unless an outlet is nearby. Your device will recognize the available connection as Action III. If you know the functions of bass, treble, and volume, you've got it mastered. It doesn't get any easier. Being an AC powered unit, it does appear to play considerably louder than a rechargeable speaker. It has excellent bass and crystal clear highs coming from twin tweeters. The midrange seems to be just a bit subdued. That's personally just how I like it, but an extra tone or contour control like the ones you find on Marshall amps would be a plus for some listeners. I‚Äôve yet to experience any issues with static and I rate it five stars based on its tone and cool looks.

I love OBSBOT products. I own three cameras all together going back no just over two years, and all three are excellent and dependable.

Most importantly, the software you can get from OBSBOT (simply called OBSBOT Webcam which replaces their earlier software called Tinycam) has vastly improved over the last year or so, to the point I consider it an absolute must for these cameras (but it doesn't slow down, crash, or otherwise behave funny in Windows 10 or 11).

You can also get an affordable remote which I have as well, and it works too -

I've used, since the pandemic began, well over a dozen total webcams from different manufacturers. These include bigger names like Logitech, Wirestorm, Yealink, and Boom, and many lesser known brands (some of which have been alright!). Overall, I consider OBSBOT my favorite. All manufacturers of dedicated Webcams seem to "create" a unique look and have their own standard for contrast, brightness, sharpness, and so forth. My impression of OBSBOT is that it's not heavy handed one way or the other, but does have an overall darker exposure than many if not most. So, you may have to tweak your setting in your software that uses the webcam (like Zoom, Teams, etc) or use the OBSBOT Webcam software for that which works well. I like that it doesn't try too hard to make things overly bright and "beautiful" by making my face look plastic and overly smooth like some seem to do.

I would not say the picture quality is astonishing - but excellent for a webcam. Frankly, I think Logitech has picture quality dialed pretty good, if that's the MOST important aspect - but for the price you basically can't beat it if PTZ is a must for you (it really is for me). The software makes controlling the camera even during meetings a breeze. And, yes, you can create and save fixed angle/zoom/tilt in the software (but it'll have to be running in the background to work reliably in your app of choice).

Also, while you don't see a "privacy cover" that's easy - tilt the lens down towards the main body and poof, you've put it to sleep. While not as reliable as a hard cover, it works just fine (just know that if you click to turn on your camera in say Zoom, it'll turn the camera on or wake it). You can also tell it to go to sleep in the app including how long to stay on if not in use.

Comes with a very nice, and I mean VERY nice zippered case that'll hold everything but the little tripod it comes with. I don't use the tripod but do have many other much taller/bigger tripods I do use with it. I've never actually used the monitor mount but it's quite strong and functional too (I just prefer stands or tripods for control).

Finally, the internal microphone is legions better than most webcam microphones. Seriously. As in, actually dependable and usable. That said, I almost never use it as I have multiple dedicated microphones I prefer to use. But, it really is usable compared to nearly every other built-in webcam mic I've every tried - so if that's important to you, know that the microphone is fine (but built-in webcam microphones simply won't ever improve on dedicated high-quality microphones made for personal or conference room use in my opinion).

One big selling point with OBSBOT is the gesture control. Sorry, I don't use it. I love this camera for the quality it has in the optics, PTZ control, and software. That said, the gestures do work and work as advertised (yes, I've tried them - they're just not my thing).

If you need a very good 4K PTZ webcam at a great price - even for a high quality conference room set up - you should consider OBSBOT.

I paid full price for the Amazon fabric case for my Kindle Scribe after trying out a cheap plasticky case and being disappointed in how it looked and functioned. But those were early days for the Scribe and new cases are popping up much more frequently.

That leads me to this case. I did not need another Scribe case but this one intrigued me not only because of the fun colors but because of a different approach to the stand and pen holder than the other cheaper case I'd tried or the Amazon case. What I love about the Amazon case is that it's thin and can prop up the reader for hands-free use. I also love that the flap attaches magnetically to the back of the case when you're holding it in your hands. But what I hate about the case is that you really have to pay attention to how you pick it up and open it. I've dropped the Scribe twice, once trying to remove it and the second time simply opening the case. There isn't anything holding it in place but magnets so if you detach them just right it comes a house of cards that instantly falls apart.

This case addresses all of those shortcomings. It places the Scribe inside the case and all sides are well-covered so it won't fall out accidentally. The pen holder is on the side where I'm used to pen holders being on e-ink note-taking devices. And most importantly, it also props up the reader for hands-free use and the flap also attaches magnetically to the back of the case when you're holding it. There is even a little slot to stick your hand to make it less likely that you'll drop it. I love this case and it is replacing my Amazon case. It isn't perfect; the front flap can shift a little and the hand grip could be a little bigger. But these aren't deal breakers for me.

Now, I will say that there is still a place for the Amazon case. If you prefer that your cases be as slim as possible, do know that this one is thicker and heavier than the Amazon case. But if you're OK with a little extra girth, I think this case is great and is priced very nicely for what you get.

Having used a number of light sets, I have to say this one stands out above the others for a number of reasons. Starting with the tripods, the construction is superior over any similar priced devices. Instead of rivets, each joint is connected with screws and nylon locking nuts and when opening and closing the tripod base, it feels surprisingly precise. The locking knobs are large and tighten in one-half turn. The tubes extended stiffly at first but became smoother with use and when extended at a measured maximum height of 52‚Äù. With the light and a phone attached, the unit remained stable.

Included in the light set are two sets of 9 colored filters, that can be slipped into a filter slot on the front of each light. The lights are powered via a standard a 5v USB power supply and can be used anywhere you want by powering them using a portable standard phone power pack. Lighting intensity is adjusted using up/down buttons located on the on/off switch and I found battery power consumption to be modest even at the highest lighting settings. (I am using a 20,000 mAh power pack)

Also included in the set are two phone holders that can be attached to the uprights. They worked well and kept my iPhone 13 tightly secured. In addition, two, 360-degree ball-head camera mounts are included allowing the lights to be aimed in any direction.

Final thoughts: This is a pretty amazing set of lights for the price. The set includes two sets of 9 colored filters, quality constructed tripods, two ball-head camera mounts, two phone holders and two 1000 lumen LED lights, (not measured), adjustable from 10-100% intensity, and a working height from 17‚Äù to 52‚Äù! I wish a carry bag was included, but I‚Äôm not going to knock the manufacturer as they have provided a quality system at a low price.

I am a frequent user of canned air and living in the Southwest I try to have a can of canned air at the ready all the time.  Since I use canned air all the time replacing them has become an expense I have started to really notice and I needed to find a way to cut back (financially) but I still need to be able to dust and clean things when necessary.  I have done some research on several of these cordless, compressed air dusters and this one really stood out from all the others.  The first and most important was its powerful 110000RPM capable motor.  This allows for air flow much higher than most of the other units on the market and allows for cleaning in between keyboard keys, dusting off motherboard fans and general daily maintenance of most products.  Secondly, is the 7800mAh battery which allows me to charge this unit up and it can hold charge (for my use) for weeks before I need to recharge it.  It has three speeds and a light at the from that helps when cleaning things in dark spaces.  This is a must have for those, like me, who want a great canned air replacement.

It's durable and well made, but it DOES need an outdoor antenna (wire will do nicely) and a good counterpoise to receive stable signals, otherwise "Clear Channel" AM stations on any band give erratic receive volume and clarity.  I found that 10 meters (33 feet) of wire under the eaves of the building as the antenna, plus 10 meters of wire forming a rectangle upon the legs of the bed as the "ground", settles things down nicely.  (A BNC male to dual binding post adapter helps.)  The battery holds a good charge, delivering at least overnight listening, and charges quickly from a USB outlet.  I did not give this device five stars because its operation is digital, but the wait between dial change and sound resumption is faster than most such radios costing quite a bit more.  Now if international short-wave stations would come back, we could get fake news from everywhere!

[[VIDEOID:5be99a112b58fea85ee9ed1ef694bfc6]] This review is for the NEWCARE HDMI 2.1 4x1 switch, which allows a single HDMI 2.1 input on a TV or monitor to easily switch between up to four HDMI sources, such as computers, game consoles, set-top boxes, etc. In terms of behavior, the active input is electronically coupled to the output while the others are in a disconnected state. Every time you switch inputs, the link needs to be re-trained, so it will take a few seconds for the picture to appear and stabilize. Overall, this product is easy to set up and works as expected. Besides switching capabilities, a secondary benefit of this product is that it effectively works as an extender, allowing you to get two HDMI cables worth of length.

I tested the NEWCARE HDMI 2.1 switch with a 4K@144Hz [[ASIN:B09885HV8C gaming monitor]], an [[ASIN:B0BP4XWWXL Windows 11 laptop]] with integrated Radeon 680M graphics, and a [[ASIN:B0B57T77H3 USB-C to HDMI 2.1 adapter]]. With this configuration, I could utilize the gaming monitor's full capabilities, verifying that HDMI 2.1 FRL signaling was indeed supported. I also connected a few HDMI 2.0b devices and was able to switch between the inputs without drama.

The NEWCARE HDMI 2.1 switch also features an IR remote control, and it comes with an optional IR receiver just in case this switch is hidden inside a media cabinet, etc. The product is USB-powered using the included USB-A to barrel connector cable, and with a rated power consumption of only 3W, a TV or game console's USB port can easily power it. This product does not come with any HDMI cables.

Notes:
1) The switching button is a clicky mechanical type that's satisfying to press. The indicator LEDs are blue and they are thankfully not very bright.
